<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Community Forest</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Background: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Since 2009 </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Community Forest has been in negotiations with Forestry Commission Scotland to purchase/ lease </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Forest through the National Forest Land Scheme. FCS deems </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Forest to be ‘surplus land’ and is therefore looking to sell the forest as part of its ‘repositioning programme’. A full summary of what this has involved over the last 4 and a half years is provided in Annex 1 attached. There are a wide range of issues that require to be resolved around State Aids (please refer to our experience at the bottom of Page 3) and interpretation of the Treasury Finance Manual amongst other things but we would like to raise a number of specific issues around the Treasury rules and the valuation of the land and the forest as this may be an area where the Scottish Affairs Committee can contribute.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Key Points:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Most public sector organisations have concluded that Treasury rules require public land to be disposed of (or leased) only at ‘full open market value’. Open market value is currently set by the district </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">valuer</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> or some other independent valuation expert. This is achieved very much on the basis of a set of rules which in forestry relate to how much income/profit can be generated by the asset and also to an extent how much the market is willing to pay. This latter point often relates to a whole series of complex tax benefits including no inheritance tax, capital gains tax, income or corporation tax liabilities and also to the status that land (with or without trees) as an asset holds in the UK - it is seen as a safe and therefore attractive investment. Many of these tax benefits will never be fully realised by community based organisations and therefore we would ascribe no ‘hope’ or market value to them. At no time in this process is any account taken of what the community as an owner may wish to achieve through the land in terms of delivering public benefits - no value is placed on environmental or social outcomes despite the public benefit these can bring.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">One way perhaps of reducing the market value should a community wish to secure a piece of publicly owned land would be to constrain potential development or hope value by indicating that there would be an expectation that certain social and environmental outcomes would be delivered which then constrains the opportunities for unfettered development which again form part of the valuation process.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">A term frequently used by public organisations throughout the land disposal process is the need to achieve 'best value for the public purse'. This</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">is consistently interpreted, in the context of sale of public land, as a financial consideration only and not in the wider context of achieving best value through quality, or additional benefits such as retention of local jobs etc. Another way of coming to the establishment of a reasonable price to be paid for an asset could be to assign values to the range of social and environmental and indeed local economic benefits that could be delivered post transfer. This value could then be 'subtracted' from any finance only valuation?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:2.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Annex 1: </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Community Forest – A Timeline</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In February 2009 Forestry Commission Scotland advised </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Strathglass</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Community Council in Cannich that it would be putting </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Forest on the market as it was deemed surplus land.  Someone from SCC contacted a member of </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Kilmorack</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Community Council to inform them of this. For some years FCS had been writing to the wrong community council and so this was the first communication the community received regarding </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Forest. KCC then alerted local residents and contact was made directly with FCS.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Scottish Law requires that such sales are offered to the community first and a public meeting organised by the community took place at </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Kilmorack</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Hall to discuss the situation on 25 March 2009.  After a 100% vote in favour, volunteers were sought to form a steering group.  Representatives from HIE and FCS were invited to be present at the meeting.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In order to meet National Forest Land Scheme requirements the community needed to constitute a steering committee, consult local residents, produce a feasibility study and a business plan, define its boundary and ballot the community to seek their approval.  From a standing start the community was given 140 days to undertake all this work and submit their application to the NFLS. This was over the summer period when the majority of residents were on holiday.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Funds (£10,000) were sourced from HIE and The Highland Council to finance the production of a feasibility study and 5 year business plan in June 2009  All other work was undertaken by the steering committee.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The initial confirmation of interest was lodged with the Forestry Commission 19 May 2009</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Community Consultation hosted by Bell Ingram took place at </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Kilmorack</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Hall on 29 June 2009 and was followed by a community postal survey</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Feasibility Study was presented to a Public Meeting at </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Kilmorack</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Hall on 17 August 2009</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">A Forest Walk took place on Sunday 23 August 2009 where approx fifty members of the community took part.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The community ballot was taken and the result showed outstanding support for the acquisition. This was despite the ballot having to take place in two parts due to conflicting advice from Highland Council and FCS.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The application to purchase under the National Forest Land Scheme was delivered to the Forestry Commission on the 8 September 2009</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The NFLS application was approved and the community were given 18-months (until 17 June 2011) to raise the £690,000 purchase price</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Community Forest company was formed on 9 February 2010 and was granted Charitable Status on 30 June 2010 as registered Scottish charity, no: SC041614</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In June 2010 with the Scottish Land Fund dried up, the BIG Lottery issued revised guidelines for community asset purchase clearly excluding grants for the purchase of publicly-owned assets.  At this time there were no publicly backed funds available to communities for land or forestry purchases.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Community Forest needed to investigate private fundraising avenues and so further funding (£10,000) was sourced from LEADER and The Highland Council to create a new website, issue membership and pledge forms to the community and revise the business plan to flesh out the social enterprise and financial sustainability elements as had been advised by HIE.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In November 2010, in recognition of the lack of purchase funding available, FCS issued guidelines for communities seeking to take a long term lease on a forest.  After due consideration the Board of </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Community Forest applied to the NFLS for permission to investigate this option and in May 2011, the NFLS granted an 18-month extension for this purpose.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In September 2011 financial support was secured from Forestry Commission Scotland though their Community </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Seedcorn</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Fund (£2,900) and in December 2011 the Valuation Office Agency were engaged to carry-out an indicative non-binding valuation using the FCS rental methodology.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> This would serve a dual purpose of investigating the methodology whilst producing an indicative figure for use in the revised business plan.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The work carried out by the VOA and analysed by Community Woodlands Scotland clearly demonstrated that the published rental methodology resulted in a punitively high annual rent that no community group could afford.  FCS accepted the problems with the methodology and agreed to extend the </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Community Forest NFLS deadline for as long as it took them to come forward with a new methodology.  FCS published the revised lease guidance in November 2012, over 6 months after they were presented with the information showing their initial proposals were flawed.  </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Community Forest was granted an extension of its NFLS deadline to June 2013.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Meanwhile, in June 2012 the Scottish Government announced the re-launch of the Scottish Land Fund.  </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Community Forest immediately approached HIE to register an interest in the fund. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Recognising that there would be a lot of work involved in completing a SLF application and pulling together match funding in a relatively short time </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Community Forest applied to HIE, FCS and The Highland Council for grants to allow a development worker to be taken on under contract.  These grants (£15,000) were approved and Lorna Campbell was appointed in August 2012.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Also in August 2012, </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Community Forest were given very encouraging information about the likelihood of success if they were to apply to the SLF and also a suggestion on how much they should ask for.   Everything was very positive.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">However, within a few weeks of that meeting HIE started to sound warnings about EU State Aid regulations.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> These rules are designed to prevent member states providing grants to companies and organisation which would then have a commercial advantage as result.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> They are intended to ensure a fair and open market and a level playing field across the EU.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> They are an extremely blunt instrument and open to interpretation by member states.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> It transpires that the Scottish Government have become ‘nervous’ about providing grants in the forestry and agriculture sector which may contravene state aid regulations and so HIE have now confirmed that a grant to </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Community Forest would be subject to state aid limits.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> This means that an application to the SLF right now would only get a maximum of 20% of the purchase price leaving in the region of £550k+ to find.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> This is a non-starter.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Since the Autumn of HIE have been investigating the possibility of setting up a scheme which would allow the SLF to provide up to 100% grants to forestry projects if the purpose of the project was conservation with any trading activity being secondary to that primary aim.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> On the clear advice of HIE back in 2009, this is not how the </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> project is currently presented.  It is in fact a reversal on everything </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Community Forest have been told to date about the need to be a sustainable social enterprise.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> In many ways this new scheme would be even better than the original SLF grant discussed in August.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> The trouble is that right now it is just a theory.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> HIE are in discussion with the Scottish Government about setting the scheme up but it will need approval from Brussels.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">  12 months since it was first mooted there are still no timescales for a launch of this scheme.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In May 2013, ACF received the VOA report setting out the ground rent payable to FCS under the revised lease methodology.  The figure was £7,800 p.a.  Although not high on the face of it, the methodology is designed to ‘protect the taxpayers interest’ and so also gives FCS 80% of the profit from any timber harvesting for the first 5 years of community management.  When the ground rent and timber harvesting were fed into a </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">cashflow</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> it was clear that ACF would not be a financially viable community enterprise without being dependent on charitable fundraising.  Given the aim of community ownership is to give back to and benefit the community, having to fundraise to sustain it was seen as counter-productive and ACF entered discussions with FCS over the second methodology.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In July 2013, FCS made it absolutely clear that the methodology was not up for negotiation even if no communities were able to make it work financially.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">However, at the same meeting FCS suggested a partial purchase / partial lease scenario that could work uniquely for </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.  This was welcomed and is currently being investigated with the aid of a further £4,200 grant from FCS.  However, it was noted by ACF that the solution was not transferable to other communities and so underlying flaws in the SLF and the FCS lease methodology remain a significant hurdle to community ownership and management of forestry.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In summary, after over 4 years and in excess of £40,000 (excluding public sector staff and voluntary sector contributions in kind)  the community of Lower </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Strathglass</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> is no nearer owning </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aigas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Forest than they were at the start. The community remains committed to the project and when open events are held they attract good turn outs. The forest continues to be used informally by a wide range of individuals and groups. We remain optimistic that the community can secure management if not ownership of the site in the near future and be able to start delivering the wide range of public benefits planned.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p></div></body></html>